The price-to-earnings ratio is an indicator of the company's value. It indicates how much an investor would have to pay per share for $\$1$ of the company's earnings. This can be used to solve for the stock price using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Stock price}&=\text{Price-to-earnings ratio} \times\text{Earnings per share}
\end{aligned}$$

In order to solve this, we must first calculate the return on equity which can be done using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Return on Equity}&=\dfrac{\text{Net Income}}{\text{Equity}}
\end{aligned}$$

Substituting the values, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Return on Equity}&=\dfrac{\$815,000}{\$6,800,000}\\[15 pt]
&=0.11985
\end{aligned}$$

The return on equity of this is $0.11985$ or $11.985\%$.

From this value, we can now solve for the retention ratio which is the percentage of the earnings that is retained. This can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Retention Ratio}&=1-\dfrac{\text{Dividends}}{\text{Net Income}}
\end{aligned}$$

Substituting the values, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Retention Ratio}&=1-\dfrac{\$285,000}{\$815,000}\\[15 pt]
&=0.6503
\end{aligned}$$

The retention ratio for this is $0.6503$ or $65.03\%$.

To properly solve for the earnings for the next year, we must solve for the sustainable growth rate. The sustainable growth rate is how much growth is profitable for the company in the long run. This can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Sustainable Growth Rate}&=\dfrac{\text{Return on Equity}\times\text{Retention Ratio}}{1-(\text{Return on Equity}\times\text{Retention Ratio})}
\end{aligned}$$

Substituting the values, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Sustainable Growth Rate}&=\dfrac{0.11985 \times 0.6503}{1-(0.11985 \times 0.6503)}\\[15 pt]
&=0.08453
\end{aligned}$$

The sustainable growth rate for the company is $0.08453$ or $8.453\%$.

Now that we have the income for next year, we can solve for the earnings per share using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Earnings per Share}&=\dfrac{\text{Income Next Year}}{\text{Number of Shares}}
\end{aligned}$$

Substituting the values, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Earnings per Share}&=\dfrac{\$883,891.95}{245,000}\\[15 pt]
&=\$3.6077
\end{aligned}$$

The earnings per share of the company for next year is $\$3.6077$.
